Despite companies like Facebook and Google trying to flag the more widely spread fraudulent news, some of it is unavoidable.
With that in mind, we’re correcting the record on some of the more common coronavirus myths being shared right now.
“Other medications that have been promoted as miracle cures for coronavirus have not held up to closer scrutiny either.
Blow drying your face and nose doesn’t helpA persistent myth is that hot air or saunas can kill off coronavirus.
The national medical director of NHS England, Stephen Powis, told Reuters that any claim of a connection between 5G and coronavirus is “utter rubbish”.